A reporter asked me to summarize the state of the Alt Right post Charlottesville, and I replied thusly;

The alt right is fractured to say the least of it. The violence, slander, prosecutions, and lawsuits understandably scared a lot of people and created a great deal of finger pointing over who was to blame. Being an ethnocentric as opposed to an ideological movement, there were always competing factions trying to push their ideas to the front of the agenda, and some of them used the chaos as an opportunity to push their own agenda and destroy their rivals.Â 

There was no definitive leader going into Charlottesville, just a series of figureheads and entertainers who people looked to for direction. With all that has happened, nobody really wants to emerge as the leader, because whoever does so emerge will be targeted for violence and persecution. Now thousands of angry White men are looking for that leader to come forward, and the world should certainly hope a responsible person arises to meet that demand, because he will be wielding a great deal of power.

It seems as though Barry Goldwater may have been onto something when he said;

I would remind you that extremism in the defense of liberty is no vice.

And let me remind you also that moderation in the pursuit of justice is no virtue.
